{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_31dc9ffa36594290a7183d83","type":"tool_result","content":"1\tRobot Framework\n2\t===============\n3\t\n4\t.. contents::\n5\t   :local:\n6\t\n7\tIntroduction\n8\t------------\n9\t\n10\t`Robot Framework <http://robotframework.org>`_ |r| is a generic open source\n11\tautomation framework for acceptance testing, acceptance test driven\n12\tdevelopment (ATDD), and robotic process automation (RPA). It has simple plain\n13\ttext syntax and it can be extended easily with generic and custom libraries.\n14\t\n15\tRobot Framework is operating system and application independent. It is\n16\timplemented using `Python <http://python.org>`_ which is also the primary\n17\tlanguage to extend it. The framework has a rich ecosystem around it consisting\n18\tof various generic libraries and tools that are developed as separate projects.\n19\tFor more information about Robot Framework and the ecosystem, see\n20\thttp://robotframework.org.\n21\t\n22\tRobot Framework project is hosted on GitHub_ where you can find source code,\n23\tan issue tracker, and some further documentation. Downloads are hosted on PyPI_.\n24\t\n25\tRobot Framework development is sponsored by non-profit `Robot Framework Foundation\n26\t<http://robotframework.org/foundation>`_. If you are using the framework\n27\tand benefiting from it, consider joining the foundation to help maintaining\n28\tthe framework and developing it further.\n29\t\n30\t.. _GitHub: https://github.com/robotframework/robotframework\n31\t.. _PyPI: https://pypi.python.org/pypi/robotframework\n32\t\n33\t.. image:: https://img.shields.io/pypi/v/robotframework.svg?label=version\n34\t   :target: https://pypi.python.org/pypi/robotframework\n35\t   :alt: Latest version\n36\t\n37\t.. image:: https://img.shields.io/pypi/l/robotframework.svg\n38\t   :target: http://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0.html\n39\t   :alt: License\n40\t\n41\tInstallation\n42\t------------\n43\t\n44\tIf you already have Python_ with `pip <https://pip.pypa.io>`_ installed,\n45\tyou can simply run::\n46\t\n47\t    pip install robotframework\n48\t\n49\tFor more detailed installation instructions, including installing Python, see\n50\t`<INSTALL.rst>`__.\n51\t\n52\tRobot Framework requires Python 3.8 or newer and runs also on `PyPy <http://pypy.org>`_.\n53\tThe latest version that supports Python 3.6 and 3.7 is `Robot Framework 6.1.1`__.\n54\tIf you need to use Python 2, `Jython <http://jython.org>`_ or\n55\t`IronPython <http://ironpython.net>`_, you can use `Robot Framework 4.1.3`__.\n56\t\n57\t__ https://github.com/robotframework/robotframework/tree/v6.1.1#readme\n58\t__ https://github.com/robotframework/robotframework/tree/v4.1.3#readme\n59\t\n60\tExample\n61\t-------\n62\t\n63\tBelow is a simple example test case for testing login to some system.\n64\tYou can find more examples with links to related demo projects from\n65\thttp://robotframework.org.\n66\t\n67\t.. code:: robotframework\n68\t\n69\t    *** Settings ***\n70\t    Documentation     A test suite with a single test for valid login.\n71\t    ...\n72\t    ...               This test has a workflow that is created using keywords in\n73\t    ...               the imported resource file.\n74\t    Resource          login.resource\n75\t\n76\t    *** Test Cases ***\n77\t    Valid Login\n78\t        Open Browser To Login Page\n79\t        Input Username    demo\n80\t        Input Password    mode\n81\t        Submit Credentials\n82\t        Welcome Page Should Be Open\n83\t        [Teardown]    Close Browser\n84\t\n85\tUsage\n86\t-----\n87\t\n88\tTests (or tasks) are executed from the command line using the ``robot``\n89\tcommand or by executing the ``robot`` module directly like ``python -m robot`` .\n90\t\n91\tThe basic usage is giving a path to a test (or task) file or directory as an\n92\targument with possible command line options before the path::\n93\t\n94\t    robot tests.robot\n95\t    robot --variable BROWSER:Firefox --outputdir results path/to/tests/\n96\t\n97\tAdditionally, there is the ``rebot`` tool for combining results and otherwise\n98\tpost-processing outputs::\n99\t\n100\t    rebot --name Example output1.xml output2.xml\n101\t\n102\tRun ``robot --help`` and ``rebot --help`` for more information about the command\n103\tline usage. For a complete reference manual see `Robot Framework User Guide`_.\n104\t\n105\tDocumentation\n106\t-------------\n107\t\n108\t- `Robot Framework User Guide\n109\t  <http://robotframework.org/robotframework/#user-guide>`_\n110\t- `Standard libraries\n111\t  <http://robotframework.org/robotframework/#standard-libraries>`_\n112\t- `API documentation <http://robot-framework.readthedocs.org>`_\n113\t- `General documentation <http://robotframework.org/>`_\n114\t\n115\tSupport and Contact\n116\t-------------------\n117\t\n118\t- `Slack <http://slack.robotframework.org/>`_\n119\t- `Forum <https://forum.robotframework.org/>`_\n120\t- `robotframework-users\n121\t  <https://groups.google.com/group/robotframework-users/>`_ mailing list\n122\t\n123\tContributing\n124\t------------\n125\t\n126\tInterested to contribute to Robot Framework? Great! In that case it is a good\n127\tstart by looking at the `<CONTRIBUTING.rst>`__. If you\n128\tdo not already have an issue you would like to work on, you can check\n129\tissues with `good new issue`__ and `help wanted`__ labels.\n130\t\n131\tRemember also that there are many other tools and libraries in the wider\n132\t`Robot Framework ecosystem <http://robotframework.org>`_ that you can\n133\tcontribute to!\n134\t\n135\t__ https://github.com/robotframework/robotframework/issues?q=is%3Aissue+is%3Aopen+label%3A%22good+first+issue%22\n136\t__ https://github.com/robotframework/robotframework/issues?q=is%3Aissue+is%3Aopen+label%3A%22help+wanted%22\n137\t\n138\tLicense and Trademark\n139\t---------------------\n140\t\n141\tRobot Framework is open source software provided under the `Apache License 2.0`__.\n142\tRobot Framework documentation and other similar content use the\n143\t`Creative Commons Attribution 3.0 Unported`__ license. Most libraries and tools\n144\tin the ecosystem are also open source, but they may use different licenses.\n145\t\n146\tRobot Framework trademark is owned by `Robot Framework Foundation`_.\n147\t\n148\t__ http://apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0\n149\t__ http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/3.0\n150\t\n151\t.. |r| unicode:: U+00AE\n152\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"4994e1f6-1805-4261-a830-b70345874940","uuid":"f995fe43-5a0b-4530-bb14-558a5e7e0061","timestamp":"2026-04-09T02:38:16.794Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/README.rst","content":"Robot Framework\n===============\n\n.. contents::\n   :local:\n\nIntroduction\n------------\n\n`Robot Framework <http://robotframework.org>`_ |r| is a generic open source\nautomation framework for acceptance testing, acceptance test driven\ndevelopment (ATDD), and robotic process automation (RPA). It has simple plain\ntext syntax and it can be extended easily with generic and custom libraries.\n\nRobot Framework is operating system and application independent. It is\nimplemented using `Python <http://python.org>`_ which is also the primary\nlanguage to extend it. The framework has a rich ecosystem around it consisting\nof various generic libraries and tools that are developed as separate projects.\nFor more information about Robot Framework and the ecosystem, see\nhttp://robotframework.org.\n\nRobot Framework project is hosted on GitHub_ where you can find source code,\nan issue tracker, and some further documentation. Downloads are hosted on PyPI_.\n\nRobot Framework development is sponsored by non-profit `Robot Framework Foundation\n<http://robotframework.org/foundation>`_. If you are using the framework\nand benefiting from it, consider joining the foundation to help maintaining\nthe framework and developing it further.\n\n.. _GitHub: https://github.com/robotframework/robotframework\n.. _PyPI: https://pypi.python.org/pypi/robotframework\n\n.. image:: https://img.shields.io/pypi/v/robotframework.svg?label=version\n   :target: https://pypi.python.org/pypi/robotframework\n   :alt: Latest version\n\n.. image:: https://img.shields.io/pypi/l/robotframework.svg\n   :target: http://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0.html\n   :alt: License\n\nInstallation\n------------\n\nIf you already have Python_ with `pip <https://pip.pypa.io>`_ installed,\nyou can simply run::\n\n    pip install robotframework\n\nFor more detailed installation instructions, including installing Python, see\n`<INSTALL.rst>`__.\n\nRobot Framework requires Python 3.8 or newer and runs also on `PyPy <http://pypy.org>`_.\nThe latest version that supports Python 3.6 and 3.7 is `Robot Framework 6.1.1`__.\nIf you need to use Python 2, `Jython <http://jython.org>`_ or\n`IronPython <http://ironpython.net>`_, you can use `Robot Framework 4.1.3`__.\n\n__ https://github.com/robotframework/robotframework/tree/v6.1.1#readme\n__ https://github.com/robotframework/robotframework/tree/v4.1.3#readme\n\nExample\n-------\n\nBelow is a simple example test case for testing login to some system.\nYou can find more examples with links to related demo projects from\nhttp://robotframework.org.\n\n.. code:: robotframework\n\n    *** Settings ***\n    Documentation     A test suite with a single test for valid login.\n    ...\n    ...               This test has a workflow that is created using keywords in\n    ...               the imported resource file.\n    Resource          login.resource\n\n    *** Test Cases ***\n    Valid Login\n        Open Browser To Login Page\n        Input Username    demo\n        Input Password    mode\n        Submit Credentials\n        Welcome Page Should Be Open\n        [Teardown]    Close Browser\n\nUsage\n-----\n\nTests (or tasks) are executed from the command line using the ``robot``\ncommand or by executing the ``robot`` module directly like ``python -m robot`` .\n\nThe basic usage is giving a path to a test (or task) file or directory as an\nargument with possible command line options before the path::\n\n    robot tests.robot\n    robot --variable BROWSER:Firefox --outputdir results path/to/tests/\n\nAdditionally, there is the ``rebot`` tool for combining results and otherwise\npost-processing outputs::\n\n    rebot --name Example output1.xml output2.xml\n\nRun ``robot --help`` and ``rebot --help`` for more information about the command\nline usage. For a complete reference manual see `Robot Framework User Guide`_.\n\nDocumentation\n-------------\n\n- `Robot Framework User Guide\n  <http://robotframework.org/robotframework/#user-guide>`_\n- `Standard libraries\n  <http://robotframework.org/robotframework/#standard-libraries>`_\n- `API documentation <http://robot-framework.readthedocs.org>`_\n- `General documentation <http://robotframework.org/>`_\n\nSupport and Contact\n-------------------\n\n- `Slack <http://slack.robotframework.org/>`_\n- `Forum <https://forum.robotframework.org/>`_\n- `robotframework-users\n  <https://groups.google.com/group/robotframework-users/>`_ mailing list\n\nContributing\n------------\n\nInterested to contribute to Robot Framework? Great! In that case it is a good\nstart by looking at the `<CONTRIBUTING.rst>`__. If you\ndo not already have an issue you would like to work on, you can check\nissues with `good new issue`__ and `help wanted`__ labels.\n\nRemember also that there are many other tools and libraries in the wider\n`Robot Framework ecosystem <http://robotframework.org>`_ that you can\ncontribute to!\n\n__ https://github.com/robotframework/robotframework/issues?q=is%3Aissue+is%3Aopen+label%3A%22good+first+issue%22\n__ https://github.com/robotframework/robotframework/issues?q=is%3Aissue+is%3Aopen+label%3A%22help+wanted%22\n\nLicense and Trademark\n---------------------\n\nRobot Framework is open source software provided under the `Apache License 2.0`__.\nRobot Framework documentation and other similar content use the\n`Creative Commons Attribution 3.0 Unported`__ license. Most libraries and tools\nin the ecosystem are also open source, but they may use different licenses.\n\nRobot Framework trademark is owned by `Robot Framework Foundation`_.\n\n__ http://apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0\n__ http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/3.0\n\n.. |r| unicode:: U+00AE\n","numLines":152,"startLine":1,"totalLines":152}}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_30a9d83836434757a70bc913","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t[tool.black]\n2\tline_length = 88\n3\t# When we add [project] with requires-python, remove this and Ruff's target-version\n4\ttarget-version = [\"py38\", \"py39\", \"py310\", \"py311\", \"py312\", \"py313\"]\n5\t\n6\t[tool.ruff]\n7\ttarget-version = \"py38\"\n8\t\n9\t[tool.ruff.lint]\n10\textend-select = [\"I\"]  # imports\n11\tignore = [\"E731\"]  # lambda assignment\n12\t\n13\t[tool.ruff.lint.pyflakes]\n14\t# Needed due to https://github.com/astral-sh/ruff/issues/9298\n15\textend-generics = [\"robot.model.body.BaseBranches\"]\n16\t\n17\t[tool.ruff.lint.isort]\n18\t# Ruff is used to sort and fix imports first. Multiline imports are organized so\n19\t# that each item is on its own line. This is same as the Vertical Hanging Indent\n20\t# mode with isort.\n21\tcombine-as-imports = true\n22\torder-by-type = false\n23\t\n24\t[tool.isort]\n25\t# isort is used after Ruff to sort \"normal\" imports so that multiline imports use\n26\t# the Hanging Grid Grouped mode. Files contained redundant import aliases denoting\n27\t# module/package API are excluded. For details about multiline modes see:\n28\t# https://pycqa.github.io/isort/docs/configuration/multi_line_output_modes.html\n29\tmulti_line_output = 5\n30\textend_skip = [\"__init__.py\", \"src/robot/api/parsing.py\"]\n31\tcombine_as_imports = true\n32\torder_by_type = false\n33\tline_length = 88\n34\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"4994e1f6-1805-4261-a830-b70345874940","uuid":"da3552ca-79ea-4587-88b9-9b242164f4a6","timestamp":"2026-04-09T02:38:16.795Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/pyproject.toml","content":"[tool.black]\nline_length = 88\n# When we add [project] with requires-python, remove this and Ruff's target-version\ntarget-version = [\"py38\", \"py39\", \"py310\", \"py311\", \"py312\", \"py313\"]\n\n[tool.ruff]\ntarget-version = \"py38\"\n\n[tool.ruff.lint]\nextend-select = [\"I\"]  # imports\nignore = [\"E731\"]  # lambda assignment\n\n[tool.ruff.lint.pyflakes]\n# Needed due to https://github.com/astral-sh/ruff/issues/9298\nextend-generics = [\"robot.model.body.BaseBranches\"]\n\n[tool.ruff.lint.isort]\n# Ruff is used to sort and fix imports first. Multiline imports are organized so\n# that each item is on its own line. This is same as the Vertical Hanging Indent\n# mode with isort.\ncombine-as-imports = true\norder-by-type = false\n\n[tool.isort]\n# isort is used after Ruff to sort \"normal\" imports so that multiline imports use\n# the Hanging Grid Grouped mode. Files contained redundant import aliases denoting\n# module/package API are excluded. For details about multiline modes see:\n# https://pycqa.github.io/isort/docs/configuration/multi_line_output_modes.html\nmulti_line_output = 5\nextend_skip = [\"__init__.py\", \"src/robot/api/parsing.py\"]\ncombine_as_imports = true\norder_by_type = false\nline_length = 88\n","numLines":34,"startLine":1,"totalLines":34}}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_fe901e20beb84a748d4895d1","type":"tool_result","content":"1\tInstallation instructions\n2\t=========================\n3\t\n4\tThese instructions cover installing `Robot Framework <https://robotframework.org>`_\n5\tand its preconditions on different operating systems. If you already have\n6\t`Python <http://python.org>`_ installed, you can install Robot Framework using\n7\tthe standard package manager `pip <https://pip.pypa.io>`_::\n8\t\n9\t    pip install robotframework\n10\t\n11\t.. contents::\n12\t   :depth: 2\n13\t   :local:\n14\t\n15\t.. START USER GUIDE IGNORE\n16\t.. Installation instructions are included also in the User Guide.\n17\t.. Following content is excluded when the UG is built.\n18\t.. default-role:: code\n19\t.. role:: file(emphasis)\n20\t.. role:: option(code)\n21\t.. END USER GUIDE IGNORE\n22\t\n23\tPython installation\n24\t-------------------\n25\t\n26\t`Robot Framework`_ is implemented using Python_, and a precondition to install it\n27\tis having Python or its alternative implementation `PyPy <https://pypy.org>`_\n28\tinstalled. Another recommended precondition is having the pip_ package manager\n29\tavailable.\n30\t\n31\tRobot Framework requires Python 3.8 or newer. The latest version that supports\n32\tPython 3.6 and 3.7 is `Robot Framework 6.1.1`__. If you need to use Python 2,\n33\t`Jython <http://jython.org>`_ or `IronPython <http://ironpython.net>`_,\n34\tyou can use `Robot Framework 4.1.3`__.\n35\t\n36\t__ https://github.com/robotframework/robotframework/blob/v6.1.1/INSTALL.rst\n37\t__ https://github.com/robotframework/robotframework/blob/v4.1.3/INSTALL.rst\n38\t\n39\tInstalling Python on Linux\n40\t~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\n41\t\n42\tOn Linux you should have suitable Python installation with pip_ available\n43\tby default. If not, you need to consult your distributions documentation\n44\tto learn how to install them. This is also true if you want to use some other\n45\tPython version than the one provided by your distribution by default.\n46\t\n47\tTo check what Python version you have installed, you can run `python --version`\n48\tcommand in a terminal:\n49\t\n50\t.. code:: bash\n51\t\n52\t  $ python --version\n53\t  Python 3.10.13\n54\t\n55\tNotice that if your distribution provides also older Python 2, running `python`\n56\tmay use that. To use Python 3, you can use `python3` command or even more version\n57\tspecific command like `python3.8`. You need to use these version specific variants\n58\talso if you have multiple Python 3 versions installed and need to pinpoint which\n59\tone to use:\n60\t\n61\t.. code:: bash\n62\t\n63\t  $ python3.11 --version\n64\t  Python 3.11.7\n65\t  $ python3.12 --version\n66\t  Python 3.12.1\n67\t\n68\tInstalling Robot Framework directly under the system provided Python\n69\thas a risk that possible problems can affect the whole Python installation\n70\tused also by the operating system itself. Nowadays\n71\tLinux distributions typically use `user installs`__ by default to avoid such\n72\tproblems, but users can also themselves decide to use `virtual environments`_.\n73\t\n74\t__ https://pip.pypa.io/en/stable/user_guide/#user-installs\n75\t\n76\tInstalling Python on Windows\n77\t~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\n78\t\n79\tOn Windows Python is not available by default, but it is easy to install.\n80\tThe recommended way to install it is using the official Windows installers available\n81\tat http://python.org. For other alternatives, such as installing from the\n82\tMicrosoft Store, see the `official Python documentation`__.\n83\t\n84\tWhen installing Python on Windows, it is recommended to add Python to PATH_\n85\tto make it and tools like pip and Robot Framework easier to execute from\n86\tthe command line. When using the `official installer`__, you just need\n87\tto select the `Add Python 3.x to PATH` checkbox on the first dialog.\n88\t\n89\tTo make sure Python installation has been successful and Python has been\n90\tadded to `PATH`, you can open the command prompt and execute `python --version`:\n91\t\n92\t.. code:: batch\n93\t\n94\t  C:\\>python --version\n95\t  Python 3.10.9\n96\t\n97\tIf you install multiple Python versions on Windows, the version that is used\n98\twhen you execute `python` is the one first in `PATH`. If you need to use others,\n99\tthe easiest way is using the `py launcher`__:\n100\t\n101\t.. code:: batch\n102\t\n103\t  C:\\>py --version\n104\t  Python 3.10.9\n105\t  C:\\>py -3.12 --version\n106\t  Python 3.12.1\n107\t\n108\t__ https://docs.python.org/3/using/windows.html\n109\t__ https://docs.python.org/3/using/windows.html#windows-full\n110\t__ https://docs.python.org/3/using/windows.html#launcher\n111\t\n112\tInstalling Python on macOS\n113\t~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\n114\t\n115\tMacOS does not provide Python 3 compatible Python version by default, so it\n116\tneeds to be installed separately. The recommended  approach is using the official\n117\tmacOS installers available at http://python.org. If you are using a package\n118\tmanager like `Homebrew <https://brew.sh/>`_, installing Python via it is\n119\tpossible as well.\n120\t\n121\tYou can validate Python installation on macOS using `python --version` like on\n122\tother operating systems.\n123\t\n124\tPyPy installation\n125\t~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\n126\t\n127\tPyPy_ is an alternative Python implementation. Its main advantage over the\n128\tstandard Python implementation is that it can be faster and use less memory,\n129\tbut this depends on the context where and how it is used. If execution speed\n130\tis important, at least testing PyPy is probably a good idea.\n131\t\n132\tInstalling PyPy is a straightforward procedure and you can find both installers\n133\tand installation instructions at http://pypy.org. To validate that PyPy installation\n134\twas successful, run `pypy --version` or `pypy3 --version`.\n135\t\n136\t.. note:: Using Robot Framework with PyPy is officially supported only on Linux.\n137\t\n138\tConfiguring `PATH`\n139\t~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\n140\t\n141\tThe `PATH environment variable`__ lists directories where commands executed in\n142\ta system are searched from. To make using Python, pip_ and Robot Framework easier\n143\tfrom the command line, it is recommended to add the Python installation directory\n144\tas well as the directory where commands like `pip` and `robot` are installed\n145\tinto `PATH`.\n146\t\n147\t__ https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PATH_(variable)\n148\t\n149\tWhen using Python on Linux or macOS, Python and tools installed with it should be\n150\tautomatically in `PATH`. If you nevertheless need to update `PATH`, you\n151\ttypically need to edit some system wide or user specific configuration file.\n152\tWhich file to edit and how depends on the operating system and you need to\n153\tconsult its documentation for more details.\n154\t\n155\tOn Windows the easiest way to make sure `PATH` is configured correctly is\n156\tsetting the `Add Python 3.x to PATH` checkbox when `running the installer`__.\n157\tTo manually modify `PATH` on Windows, follow these steps:\n158\t\n159\t1. Find `Environment Variables` under `Settings`. There are variables affecting\n160\t   the whole system and variables affecting only the current user. Modifying\n161\t   the former will require admin rights, but modifying the latter is typically\n162\t   enough.\n163\t\n164\t2. Select `PATH` (often written like `Path`) and click `Edit`. If you are\n165\t   editing user variables and `PATH` does not exist, click `New` instead.\n166\t\n167\t3. Add both the Python installation directory and the :file:`Scripts` directory\n168\t   under the installation directory into `PATH`.\n169\t\n170\t4. Exit the dialog with `Ok` to save the changes.\n171\t\n172\t5. Start a new command prompt for the changes to take effect.\n173\t\n174\t__ https://docs.python.org/3/using/windows.html#the-full-installer\n175\t\n176\tInstalling using pip\n177\t--------------------\n178\t\n179\tThese instructions cover installing Robot Framework using pip_, the standard\n180\tPython package manager. If you are using some other package manager like\n181\t`Conda <https://conda.io>`_, you can use it instead but need to study its\n182\tdocumentation for instructions.\n183\t\n184\tWhen installing Python, you typically get pip installed automatically. If\n185\tthat is not the case, you need to check the documentation of that Python\n186\tinstallation for instructions how to install it separately.\n187\t\n188\tRunning `pip` command\n189\t~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\n190\t\n191\tTypically you use pip by running the `pip` command, but on Linux you may need\n192\tto use `pip3` or even more Python version specific variant like `pip3.8`\n193\tinstead. When running `pip` or any of its variants, the pip version that is\n194\tfound first in PATH_ will be used. If you have multiple Python versions\n195\tinstalled, you may need to pinpoint which exact version you want to use.\n196\tThis is typically easiest done by running `python -m pip` and substituting\n197\t`python` with the Python version you want to use.\n198\t\n199\tTo make sure you have pip available, you can run `pip --version` or equivalent.\n200\t\n201\tExamples on Linux:\n202\t\n203\t.. code:: bash\n204\t\n205\t  $ pip --version\n206\t  pip 23.2.1 from ... (python 3.10)\n207\t  $ python3.12 -m pip --version\n208\t  pip 23.3.1 from ... (python 3.12)\n209\t\n210\tExamples on Windows:\n211\t\n212\t.. code:: batch\n213\t\n214\t  C:\\> pip --version\n215\t  pip 23.2.1 from ... (python 3.10)\n216\t  C:\\> py -m 3.12 -m pip --version\n217\t  pip 23.3.2 from ... (python 3.12)\n218\t\n219\tIn the subsequent sections pip is always run using the `pip` command. You may\n220\tneed to use some of the other approaches explained above in your environment.\n221\t\n222\tInstalling and uninstalling Robot Framework\n223\t~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\n224\t\n225\tThe easiest way to use pip is by letting it find and download packages it\n226\tinstalls from the `Python Package Index (PyPI)`__, but it can also install\n227\tpackages downloaded from the PyPI separately. The most common usages are\n228\tshown below and pip_ documentation has more information and examples.\n229\t\n230\t__ PyPI_\n231\t\n232\t.. code:: bash\n233\t\n234\t    # Install the latest version (does not upgrade)\n235\t    pip install robotframework\n236\t\n237\t    # Upgrade to the latest stable version\n238\t    pip install --upgrade robotframework\n239\t\n240\t    # Upgrade to the latest version even if it is a pre-release\n241\t    pip install --upgrade --pre robotframework\n242\t\n243\t    # Install a specific version\n244\t    pip install robotframework==7.0\n245\t\n246\t    # Install separately downloaded package (no network connection needed)\n247\t    pip install robotframework-7.0-py3-none-any.whl\n248\t\n249\t    # Install latest (possibly unreleased) code directly from GitHub\n250\t    pip install https://github.com/robotframework/robotframework/archive/master.zip\n251\t\n252\t    # Uninstall\n253\t    pip uninstall robotframework\n254\t\n255\tInstalling from source\n256\t----------------------\n257\t\n258\tAnother installation alternative is getting Robot Framework source code\n259\tand installing it using the provided `setup.py` script. This approach is\n260\trecommended only if you do not have pip_ available for some reason.\n261\t\n262\tYou can get the source code by downloading a source distribution package\n263\tfrom PyPI_ and extracting it. An alternative is cloning the GitHub_\n264\trepository and checking out the needed release tag.\n265\t\n266\tOnce you have the source code, you can install it with the following command:\n267\t\n268\t.. code:: bash\n269\t\n270\t   python setup.py install\n271\t\n272\tThe `setup.py` script accepts several arguments allowing, for example,\n273\tinstallation into a non-default location that does not require administrative\n274\trights. It is also used for creating different distribution packages. Run\n275\t`python setup.py --help` for more details.\n276\t\n277\tVerifying installation\n278\t----------------------\n279\t\n280\tTo make sure that the correct Robot Framework version has been installed, run\n281\tthe following command:\n282\t\n283\t.. code:: bash\n284\t\n285\t   $ robot --version\n286\t   Robot Framework 7.0 (Python 3.10.3 on linux)\n287\t\n288\tIf running these commands fails with a message saying that the command is\n289\tnot found or recognized, a good first step is double-checking the PATH_\n290\tconfiguration.\n291\t\n292\tIf you have installed Robot Framework under multiple Python versions,\n293\trunning `robot` will execute the one first in PATH_. To select explicitly,\n294\tyou can run `python -m robot` and substitute `python` with the right Python\n295\tversion.\n296\t\n297\t.. code:: bash\n298\t\n299\t   $ python3.12 -m robot --version\n300\t   Robot Framework 7.0 (Python 3.12.1 on linux)\n301\t\n302\t   C:\\>py -3.11 -m robot --version\n303\t   Robot Framework 7.0 (Python 3.11.7 on win32)\n304\t\n305\tDependencies\n306\t------------\n307\t\n308\tRobot Framework core functionality has no mandatory dependencies other than\n309\tPython and its standard library. Some individual features may require optional\n310\tdependencies to be installed, though. What dependencies are needed is always\n311\texplained in the relevant documentation.\n312\t\n313\tVirtual environments\n314\t--------------------\n315\t\n316\tPython `virtual environments`__ allow Python packages to be installed in\n317\tan isolated location for a particular system or application, rather than\n318\tinstalling all packages into the same global location. They have\n319\ttwo main use cases:\n320\t\n321\t- Install packages needed by different projects into their own environments.\n322\t  This avoids conflicts if projects need different versions of same packages.\n323\t\n324\t- Avoid installing everything under the global Python installation. This is\n325\t  especially important on Linux where the global Python installation may be\n326\t  used by the distribution itself and messing it up can cause severe problems.\n327\t\n328\t__ https://packaging.python.org/en/latest/guides/installing-using-pip-and-virtual-environments/#creating-a-virtual-environment\n329\t\n330\t.. _PATH: `Configuring path`_\n331\t.. _PyPI: https://pypi.org/project/robotframework\n332\t.. _GitHub: https://github.com/robotframework/robotframework\n333\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"4994e1f6-1805-4261-a830-b70345874940","uuid":"909c640d-8ed8-4f79-9b4f-cffa52baae77","timestamp":"2026-04-09T02:38:16.797Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/INSTALL.rst","content":"Installation instructions\n=========================\n\nThese instructions cover installing `Robot Framework <https://robotframework.org>`_\nand its preconditions on different operating systems. If you already have\n`Python <http://python.org>`_ installed, you can install Robot Framework using\nthe standard package manager `pip <https://pip.pypa.io>`_::\n\n    pip install robotframework\n\n.. contents::\n   :depth: 2\n   :local:\n\n.. START USER GUIDE IGNORE\n.. Installation instructions are included also in the User Guide.\n.. Following content is excluded when the UG is built.\n.. default-role:: code\n.. role:: file(emphasis)\n.. role:: option(code)\n.. END USER GUIDE IGNORE\n\nPython installation\n-------------------\n\n`Robot Framework`_ is implemented using Python_, and a precondition to install it\nis having Python or its alternative implementation `PyPy <https://pypy.org>`_\ninstalled. Another recommended precondition is having the pip_ package manager\navailable.\n\nRobot Framework requires Python 3.8 or newer. The latest version that supports\nPython 3.6 and 3.7 is `Robot Framework 6.1.1`__. If you need to use Python 2,\n`Jython <http://jython.org>`_ or `IronPython <http://ironpython.net>`_,\nyou can use `Robot Framework 4.1.3`__.\n\n__ https://github.com/robotframework/robotframework/blob/v6.1.1/INSTALL.rst\n__ https://github.com/robotframework/robotframework/blob/v4.1.3/INSTALL.rst\n\nInstalling Python on Linux\n~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\n\nOn Linux you should have suitable Python installation with pip_ available\nby default. If not, you need to consult your distributions documentation\nto learn how to install them. This is also true if you want to use some other\nPython version than the one provided by your distribution by default.\n\nTo check what Python version you have installed, you can run `python --version`\ncommand in a terminal:\n\n.. code:: bash\n\n  $ python --version\n  Python 3.10.13\n\nNotice that if your distribution provides also older Python 2, running `python`\nmay use that. To use Python 3, you can use `python3` command or even more version\nspecific command like `python3.8`. You need to use these version specific variants\nalso if you have multiple Python 3 versions installed and need to pinpoint which\none to use:\n\n.. code:: bash\n\n  $ python3.11 --version\n  Python 3.11.7\n  $ python3.12 --version\n  Python 3.12.1\n\nInstalling Robot Framework directly under the system provided Python\nhas a risk that possible problems can affect the whole Python installation\nused also by the operating system itself. Nowadays\nLinux distributions typically use `user installs`__ by default to avoid such\nproblems, but users can also themselves decide to use `virtual environments`_.\n\n__ https://pip.pypa.io/en/stable/user_guide/#user-installs\n\nInstalling Python on Windows\n~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\n\nOn Windows Python is not available by default, but it is easy to install.\nThe recommended way to install it is using the official Windows installers available\nat http://python.org. For other alternatives, such as installing from the\nMicrosoft Store, see the `official Python documentation`__.\n\nWhen installing Python on Windows, it is recommended to add Python to PATH_\nto make it and tools like pip and Robot Framework easier to execute from\nthe command line. When using the `official installer`__, you just need\nto select the `Add Python 3.x to PATH` checkbox on the first dialog.\n\nTo make sure Python installation has been successful and Python has been\nadded to `PATH`, you can open the command prompt and execute `python --version`:\n\n.. code:: batch\n\n  C:\\>python --version\n  Python 3.10.9\n\nIf you install multiple Python versions on Windows, the version that is used\nwhen you execute `python` is the one first in `PATH`. If you need to use others,\nthe easiest way is using the `py launcher`__:\n\n.. code:: batch\n\n  C:\\>py --version\n  Python 3.10.9\n  C:\\>py -3.12 --version\n  Python 3.12.1\n\n__ https://docs.python.org/3/using/windows.html\n__ https://docs.python.org/3/using/windows.html#windows-full\n__ https://docs.python.org/3/using/windows.html#launcher\n\nInstalling Python on macOS\n~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\n\nMacOS does not provide Python 3 compatible Python version by default, so it\nneeds to be installed separately. The recommended  approach is using the official\nmacOS installers available at http://python.org. If you are using a package\nmanager like `Homebrew <https://brew.sh/>`_, installing Python via it is\npossible as well.\n\nYou can validate Python installation on macOS using `python --version` like on\nother operating systems.\n\nPyPy installation\n~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\n\nPyPy_ is an alternative Python implementation. Its main advantage over the\nstandard Python implementation is that it can be faster and use less memory,\nbut this depends on the context where and how it is used. If execution speed\nis important, at least testing PyPy is probably a good idea.\n\nInstalling PyPy is a straightforward procedure and you can find both installers\nand installation instructions at http://pypy.org. To validate that PyPy installation\nwas successful, run `pypy --version` or `pypy3 --version`.\n\n.. note:: Using Robot Framework with PyPy is officially supported only on Linux.\n\nConfiguring `PATH`\n~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\n\nThe `PATH environment variable`__ lists directories where commands executed in\na system are searched from. To make using Python, pip_ and Robot Framework easier\nfrom the command line, it is recommended to add the Python installation directory\nas well as the directory where commands like `pip` and `robot` are installed\ninto `PATH`.\n\n__ https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PATH_(variable)\n\nWhen using Python on Linux or macOS, Python and tools installed with it should be\nautomatically in `PATH`. If you nevertheless need to update `PATH`, you\ntypically need to edit some system wide or user specific configuration file.\nWhich file to edit and how depends on the operating system and you need to\nconsult its documentation for more details.\n\nOn Windows the easiest way to make sure `PATH` is configured correctly is\nsetting the `Add Python 3.x to PATH` checkbox when `running the installer`__.\nTo manually modify `PATH` on Windows, follow these steps:\n\n1. Find `Environment Variables` under `Settings`. There are variables affecting\n   the whole system and variables affecting only the current user. Modifying\n   the former will require admin rights, but modifying the latter is typically\n   enough.\n\n2. Select `PATH` (often written like `Path`) and click `Edit`. If you are\n   editing user variables and `PATH` does not exist, click `New` instead.\n\n3. Add both the Python installation directory and the :file:`Scripts` directory\n   under the installation directory into `PATH`.\n\n4. Exit the dialog with `Ok` to save the changes.\n\n5. Start a new command prompt for the changes to take effect.\n\n__ https://docs.python.org/3/using/windows.html#the-full-installer\n\nInstalling using pip\n--------------------\n\nThese instructions cover installing Robot Framework using pip_, the standard\nPython package manager. If you are using some other package manager like\n`Conda <https://conda.io>`_, you can use it instead but need to study its\ndocumentation for instructions.\n\nWhen installing Python, you typically get pip installed automatically. If\nthat is not the case, you need to check the documentation of that Python\ninstallation for instructions how to install it separately.\n\nRunning `pip` command\n~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\n\nTypically you use pip by running the `pip` command, but on Linux you may need\nto use `pip3` or even more Python version specific variant like `pip3.8`\ninstead. When running `pip` or any of its variants, the pip version that is\nfound first in PATH_ will be used. If you have multiple Python versions\ninstalled, you may need to pinpoint which exact version you want to use.\nThis is typically easiest done by running `python -m pip` and substituting\n`python` with the Python version you want to use.\n\nTo make sure you have pip available, you can run `pip --version` or equivalent.\n\nExamples on Linux:\n\n.. code:: bash\n\n  $ pip --version\n  pip 23.2.1 from ... (python 3.10)\n  $ python3.12 -m pip --version\n  pip 23.3.1 from ... (python 3.12)\n\nExamples on Windows:\n\n.. code:: batch\n\n  C:\\> pip --version\n  pip 23.2.1 from ... (python 3.10)\n  C:\\> py -m 3.12 -m pip --version\n  pip 23.3.2 from ... (python 3.12)\n\nIn the subsequent sections pip is always run using the `pip` command. You may\nneed to use some of the other approaches explained above in your environment.\n\nInstalling and uninstalling Robot Framework\n~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\n\nThe easiest way to use pip is by letting it find and download packages it\ninstalls from the `Python Package Index (PyPI)`__, but it can also install\npackages downloaded from the PyPI separately. The most common usages are\nshown below and pip_ documentation has more information and examples.\n\n__ PyPI_\n\n.. code:: bash\n\n    # Install the latest version (does not upgrade)\n    pip install robotframework\n\n    # Upgrade to the latest stable version\n    pip install --upgrade robotframework\n\n    # Upgrade to the latest version even if it is a pre-release\n    pip install --upgrade --pre robotframework\n\n    # Install a specific version\n    pip install robotframework==7.0\n\n    # Install separately downloaded package (no network connection needed)\n    pip install robotframework-7.0-py3-none-any.whl\n\n    # Install latest (possibly unreleased) code directly from GitHub\n    pip install https://github.com/robotframework/robotframework/archive/master.zip\n\n    # Uninstall\n    pip uninstall robotframework\n\nInstalling from source\n----------------------\n\nAnother installation alternative is getting Robot Framework source code\nand installing it using the provided `setup.py` script. This approach is\nrecommended only if you do not have pip_ available for some reason.\n\nYou can get the source code by downloading a source distribution package\nfrom PyPI_ and extracting it. An alternative is cloning the GitHub_\nrepository and checking out the needed release tag.\n\nOnce you have the source code, you can install it with the following command:\n\n.. code:: bash\n\n   python setup.py install\n\nThe `setup.py` script accepts several arguments allowing, for example,\ninstallation into a non-default location that does not require administrative\nrights. It is also used for creating different distribution packages. Run\n`python setup.py --help` for more details.\n\nVerifying installation\n----------------------\n\nTo make sure that the correct Robot Framework version has been installed, run\nthe following command:\n\n.. code:: bash\n\n   $ robot --version\n   Robot Framework 7.0 (Python 3.10.3 on linux)\n\nIf running these commands fails with a message saying that the command is\nnot found or recognized, a good first step is double-checking the PATH_\nconfiguration.\n\nIf you have installed Robot Framework under multiple Python versions,\nrunning `robot` will execute the one first in PATH_. To select explicitly,\nyou can run `python -m robot` and substitute `python` with the right Python\nversion.\n\n.. code:: bash\n\n   $ python3.12 -m robot --version\n   Robot Framework 7.0 (Python 3.12.1 on linux)\n\n   C:\\>py -3.11 -m robot --version\n   Robot Framework 7.0 (Python 3.11.7 on win32)\n\nDependencies\n------------\n\nRobot Framework core functionality has no mandatory dependencies other than\nPython and its standard library. Some individual features may require optional\ndependencies to be installed, though. What dependencies are needed is always\nexplained in the relevant documentation.\n\nVirtual environments\n--------------------\n\nPython `virtual environments`__ allow Python packages to be installed in\nan isolated location for a particular system or application, rather than\ninstalling all packages into the same global location. They have\ntwo main use cases:\n\n- Install packages needed by different projects into their own environments.\n  This avoids conflicts if projects need different versions of same packages.\n\n- Avoid installing everything under the global Python installation. This is\n  especially important on Linux where the global Python installation may be\n  used by the distribution itself and messing it up can cause severe problems.\n\n__ https://packaging.python.org/en/latest/guides/installing-using-pip-and-virtual-environments/#creating-a-virtual-environment\n\n.. _PATH: `Configuring path`_\n.. _PyPI: https://pypi.org/project/robotframework\n.. _GitHub: https://github.com/robotframework/robotframework\n","numLines":333,"startLine":1,"totalLines":333}}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_c1352cd31e464fbe954816be","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Requirements needed for development and for building releases.\n2\t# See BUILD.rst for details about the latter\n3\tinvoke >= 0.20\n4\trellu >= 0.7, < 2\n5\tsetuptools > 75\n6\ttwine > 6\n7\twheel\n8\tdocutils\n9\tmarkdown\n10\tpygments >= 2.8\n11\tsphinx\n12\tsphinx-rtd-theme\n13\tpydantic < 2\n14\ttelnetlib-313-and-up; python_version >= \"3.13\"\n15\tblack >= 24\n16\truff\n17\tisort\n18\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"4994e1f6-1805-4261-a830-b70345874940","uuid":"62adf2bb-8c17-42b2-b080-6d0ace630e3d","timestamp":"2026-04-09T02:38:16.798Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/requirements-dev.txt","content":"# Requirements needed for development and for building releases.\n# See BUILD.rst for details about the latter\ninvoke >= 0.20\nrellu >= 0.7, < 2\nsetuptools > 75\ntwine > 6\nwheel\ndocutils\nmarkdown\npygments >= 2.8\nsphinx\nsphinx-rtd-theme\npydantic < 2\ntelnetlib-313-and-up; python_version >= \"3.13\"\nblack >= 24\nruff\nisort\n","numLines":18,"startLine":1,"totalLines":18}}}
