{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_d729e5c4ff924decb4b337f9","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t.. default-role:: code\n2\t\n3\t\n4\tRobot Framework acceptance tests\n5\t================================\n6\t\n7\tAcceptance tests for Robot Framework are naturally created using Robot\n8\tFramework itself. This folder contains all those acceptance tests and other\n9\ttest data they need.\n10\t\n11\t.. contents::\n12\t   :local:\n13\t   :depth: 2\n14\t\n15\tDirectory contents\n16\t------------------\n17\t\n18\t`<run.py>`_\n19\t    A script for executing acceptance tests. See `Running acceptance tests`_\n20\t    for further instructions.\n21\t\n22\t`<robot/>`_\n23\t    Contains the actual acceptance tests. See the `Test data`_ section for details.\n24\t\n25\t`<resources/>`_\n26\t    Resources needed by acceptance tests in the `robot` folder.\n27\t\n28\t`<testdata/>`_\n29\t    Contains tests that are run by the tests in the `robot` folder. See\n30\t    the `Test data`_ section for details.\n31\t\n32\t`<testresources/>`_\n33\t    Contains resources needed by test cases in the `testdata` folder.\n34\t    Some of these resources are also used by `unit tests <../utest/README.rst>`_.\n35\t\n36\t`<results/>`_\n37\t    The place for test execution results. This directory is generated when\n38\t    acceptance tests are executed. It is in `.gitignore` and can be safely\n39\t    deleted any time.\n40\t\n41\t`<genrunner.py>`_\n42\t    Script to generate acceptance test runners (i.e. files under the `robot`\n43\t    directory) based on the test data files (i.e. files under the `testdata`\n44\t    directory). Mainly useful if there is one-to-one mapping between tests in\n45\t    the `testdata` and `robot` directories.\n46\t\n47\t    Usage:  `atest/genrunner.py atest/testdata/path/data.robot [atest/robot/path/runner.robot]`\n48\t\n49\tRunning acceptance tests\n50\t------------------------\n51\t\n52\tRobot Framework's acceptance tests are executed using the `<run.py>`__\n53\tscript. Its usage is as follows::\n54\t\n55\t    atest/run.py [--interpreter interpreter] [--schema-validation] [options] [data]\n56\t\n57\t`data` is path (or paths) of the file or directory under the `atest/robot`\n58\tfolder to execute. If `data` is not given, all tests except for tests tagged\n59\twith `no-ci` are executed. See the `Test tags`_ section below for more\n60\tinformation about the `no-ci` tag and tagging tests in general.\n61\t\n62\tAvailable `options` are the same that can be used with Robot Framework.\n63\tSee its help (e.g. `robot --help`) for more information.\n64\t\n65\tBy default tests are executed using the same Python interpreter that is used for\n66\trunning the `run.py` script. That can be changed by using the `--interpreter` (`-I`)\n67\toption. It can be the name of the interpreter (e.g. `pypy3`) or a path to the\n68\tselected interpreter (e.g. `/usr/bin/python39`). If the interpreter itself needs\n69\targuments, the interpreter and its arguments need to be quoted (e.g. `\"py -3.9\"`).\n70\t\n71\t`--schema-validation` can be used to enable `schema validation`_ for all output.xml\n72\tfiles.\n73\t\n74\tExamples:\n75\t\n76\t.. code:: bash\n77\t\n78\t    # Execute all tests.\n79\t    atest/run.py\n80\t\n81\t    # Execute all tests using a custom interpreter.\n82\t    atest/run.py --interpreter pypy3\n83\t\n84\t    # Exclude tests requiring lxml. See the Test tags section for more information.\n85\t    atest/run.py --exclude require-lxml\n86\t\n87\t    # Exclude tests requiring manual interaction or Telnet server.\n88\t    # This is needed when executing a specified directory containing such tests.\n89\t    # If data is not specified, these tests are excluded automatically.\n90\t    atest/run.py --exclude no-ci atest/robot/standard_libraries\n91\t\n92\tThe results of the test execution are written into an interpreter specific\n93\tdirectory under the `atest/results` directory. Temporary outputs created\n94\tduring the execution are created under the system temporary directory.\n95\t\n96\tTest data\n97\t---------\n98\t\n99\tThe test data is divided into two sides, the execution side\n100\t(`atest/robot <robot>`_ directory) and the test data side\n101\t(`atest/testdata <testdata>`_ directory). The test data side contains test\n102\tcases for different features. The execution side contains the actual acceptance\n103\ttests that run the tests on the test data side and verify their results.\n104\t\n105\tThe basic mechanism to verify that a test case in the test data side is\n106\texecuted as expected is setting the expected status and possible error\n107\tmessage in its documentation. By default tests are expected to pass, but\n108\thaving `FAIL` or `SKIP` (these and subsequent markers are case sensitive) in\n109\tthe documentation changes the expectation. The text after the `FAIL` or `SKIP`\n110\tmarker is the expected error message, which, by default, must match the actual\n111\terror exactly. If the error message starts with `REGEXP:`, `GLOB:` or\n112\t`STARTS:`, the expected error is considered to be a regexp or glob pattern\n113\tmatching the actual error, or to contain the beginning of the error. All\n114\tother details can be tested also, but that logic is in the execution side.\n115\t\n116\tTest tags\n117\t---------\n118\t\n119\tThe tests on the execution side (`atest/robot`) contain tags that are used\n120\tto include or exclude them based on the platform and required dependencies.\n121\tSelecting tests based on the platform is done automatically by the `<run.py>`__\n122\tscript, but additional selection can be done by the user, for example, to\n123\tavoid running tests with dependencies_ that are not met.\n124\t\n125\tmanual\n126\t  Require manual interaction from user. Used with Dialogs library tests.\n127\t\n128\ttelnet\n129\t  Require a Telnet server with test account running on localhost. See\n130\t  `Telnet tests`_ for details.\n131\t\n132\tno-ci\n133\t  Tests which are not executed at continuous integration. Contains all tests\n134\t  tagged with `manual` or `telnet`.\n135\t\n136\trequire-yaml, require-lxml, require-screenshot\n137\t  Require specified Python module or some other external tool to be installed.\n138\t  Exclude like `--exclude require-lxml` if dependencies_ are not met.\n139\t\n140\trequire-windows, require-py3.13, ...\n141\t  Tests that require certain operating system or Python interpreter.\n142\t  Excluded automatically outside these platforms.\n143\t\n144\tno-windows, no-osx, ...\n145\t  Tests to be excluded on certain operating systems or Python interpreters.\n146\t  Excluded automatically on these platforms.\n147\t\n148\tDependencies\n149\t------------\n150\t\n151\tCertain Robot Framework features require optional external modules or tools\n152\tto be installed, and naturally tests related to these features require same\n153\tmodules/tools as well. This section lists what preconditions are needed to\n154\trun all tests successfully. See `Test tags`_ for instructions how to avoid\n155\trunning certain tests if all preconditions are not met.\n156\t\n157\tExecution side dependencies\n158\t~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\n159\t\n160\tThe execution side has some dependencies listed in `<requirements-run.txt>`__\n161\tthat needs to be installed before running tests. It is easiest to install\n162\tthem all in one go using `pip`::\n163\t\n164\t    pip install -r atest/requirements-run.txt\n165\t\n166\tTest data side dependencies\n167\t~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\n168\t\n169\tThe test data side contains the tests for various features and has more\n170\tdependencies than the execution side.\n171\t\n172\tNeeded Python modules\n173\t'''''''''''''''''''''\n174\t\n175\t- `docutils <http://docutils.sourceforge.net/>`_ is needed with tests related\n176\t  to parsing test data in reStructuredText format and with Libdoc tests\n177\t  for documentation in reST format.\n178\t- `Pygments <http://pygments.org/>`_ is needed by Libdoc tests for syntax\n179\t  highlighting.\n180\t- `PyYAML <http://pyyaml.org/>`__ is required with tests related to YAML\n181\t  variable files.\n182\t- `Pillow <https://pypi.org/project/Pillow/>`_ for taking screenshots on Windows.\n183\t- `lxml <http://lxml.de/>`__ is needed with XML library tests.\n184\t\n185\tIt is possible to install the above modules using `pip` individually, but\n186\tit is easiest to use the provided `<requirements.txt>`__ file that installs\n187\tneeded packages conditionally depending on the platform::\n188\t\n189\t    pip install -r atest/requirements.txt\n190\t\n191\tNotice that the lxml module may require compilation on Linux, which in turn\n192\tmay require installing development headers of lxml dependencies. Alternatively\n193\tlxml can be installed using a system package manager with a command like\n194\t`sudo apt-get install python-lxml`.\n195\t\n196\tScreenshot module or tool\n197\t'''''''''''''''''''''''''\n198\t\n199\tScreenshot library tests require a platform dependent module or tool that can\n200\ttake screenshots. The above instructions already covered installing Pillow_\n201\ton Windows and on OSX it is possible to use tooling provided by the operating\n202\tsystem automatically. For Linux alternatives consult the\n203\t`Screenshot library documentation`__.\n204\t\n205\t__ http://robotframework.org/robotframework/latest/libraries/Screenshot.html\n206\t\n207\tSchema validation\n208\t-----------------\n209\t\n210\toutput.xml schema\n211\t~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\n212\t\n213\tCreated output.xml has a `schema <../doc/schema>`_ that can be tested as part of\n214\tacceptance tests. The schema is always used to validate selected outputs (e.g. in\n215\t`<robot/rebot/compatibility.robot>`_), but validating all outputs would slow down\n216\texecution a bit too much.\n217\t\n218\tIt is, however, possible to enable validating all outputs by setting\n219\t`ATEST_VALIDATE_OUTPUT` environment variable to `TRUE` (case-insensitive)\n220\tor by using `--schema-validation` (`-S`) option with `atest/run.py`.\n221\tThis is recommended especially if the schema is updated or output.xml changed.\n222\t\n223\tLibdoc XML and JSON spec schemas\n224\t~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\n225\t\n226\tLibdoc can create spec files both in XML and JSON formats and they both have\n227\t`schemas <../doc/schema>`_. All generated Libdoc specs are validated automatically\n228\tin Libdoc tests.\n229\t\n230\tTelnet tests\n231\t------------\n232\t\n233\tRunning telnet tests requires some extra setup. Instructions how to run them\n234\tcan be found from `<testdata/standard_libraries/telnet/README.rst>`_.\n235\tIf you don't want to run an unprotected telnet server on your machine, you can\n236\talways skip these tests by excluding tests with a tag `telnet` or `no-ci`.\n237\t\n238\tLicense and copyright\n239\t---------------------\n240\t\n241\tAll content in the `atest` folder is under the following copyright::\n242\t\n243\t    Copyright 2008-2015 Nokia Networks\n244\t    Copyright 2016-     Robot Framework Foundation\n245\t\n246\t    Licensed under the Apache License, Version 2.0 (the \"License\");\n247\t    you may not use this file except in compliance with the License.\n248\t    You may obtain a copy of the License at\n249\t\n250\t        http://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0\n251\t\n252\t    Unless required by applicable law or agreed to in writing, software\n253\t    distributed under the License is distributed on an \"AS IS\" BASIS,\n254\t    WITHOUT WARRANTIES OR CONDITIONS OF ANY KIND, either express or implied.\n255\t    See the License for the specific language governing permissions and\n256\t    limitations under the License.\n257\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"4994e1f6-1805-4261-a830-b70345874940","uuid":"80bccc8a-e8a4-4cc2-ab73-2a78957feab0","timestamp":"2026-04-09T02:38:27.644Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/atest/README.rst","content":".. default-role:: code\n\n\nRobot Framework acceptance tests\n================================\n\nAcceptance tests for Robot Framework are naturally created using Robot\nFramework itself. This folder contains all those acceptance tests and other\ntest data they need.\n\n.. contents::\n   :local:\n   :depth: 2\n\nDirectory contents\n------------------\n\n`<run.py>`_\n    A script for executing acceptance tests. See `Running acceptance tests`_\n    for further instructions.\n\n`<robot/>`_\n    Contains the actual acceptance tests. See the `Test data`_ section for details.\n\n`<resources/>`_\n    Resources needed by acceptance tests in the `robot` folder.\n\n`<testdata/>`_\n    Contains tests that are run by the tests in the `robot` folder. See\n    the `Test data`_ section for details.\n\n`<testresources/>`_\n    Contains resources needed by test cases in the `testdata` folder.\n    Some of these resources are also used by `unit tests <../utest/README.rst>`_.\n\n`<results/>`_\n    The place for test execution results. This directory is generated when\n    acceptance tests are executed. It is in `.gitignore` and can be safely\n    deleted any time.\n\n`<genrunner.py>`_\n    Script to generate acceptance test runners (i.e. files under the `robot`\n    directory) based on the test data files (i.e. files under the `testdata`\n    directory). Mainly useful if there is one-to-one mapping between tests in\n    the `testdata` and `robot` directories.\n\n    Usage:  `atest/genrunner.py atest/testdata/path/data.robot [atest/robot/path/runner.robot]`\n\nRunning acceptance tests\n------------------------\n\nRobot Framework's acceptance tests are executed using the `<run.py>`__\nscript. Its usage is as follows::\n\n    atest/run.py [--interpreter interpreter] [--schema-validation] [options] [data]\n\n`data` is path (or paths) of the file or directory under the `atest/robot`\nfolder to execute. If `data` is not given, all tests except for tests tagged\nwith `no-ci` are executed. See the `Test tags`_ section below for more\ninformation about the `no-ci` tag and tagging tests in general.\n\nAvailable `options` are the same that can be used with Robot Framework.\nSee its help (e.g. `robot --help`) for more information.\n\nBy default tests are executed using the same Python interpreter that is used for\nrunning the `run.py` script. That can be changed by using the `--interpreter` (`-I`)\noption. It can be the name of the interpreter (e.g. `pypy3`) or a path to the\nselected interpreter (e.g. `/usr/bin/python39`). If the interpreter itself needs\narguments, the interpreter and its arguments need to be quoted (e.g. `\"py -3.9\"`).\n\n`--schema-validation` can be used to enable `schema validation`_ for all output.xml\nfiles.\n\nExamples:\n\n.. code:: bash\n\n    # Execute all tests.\n    atest/run.py\n\n    # Execute all tests using a custom interpreter.\n    atest/run.py --interpreter pypy3\n\n    # Exclude tests requiring lxml. See the Test tags section for more information.\n    atest/run.py --exclude require-lxml\n\n    # Exclude tests requiring manual interaction or Telnet server.\n    # This is needed when executing a specified directory containing such tests.\n    # If data is not specified, these tests are excluded automatically.\n    atest/run.py --exclude no-ci atest/robot/standard_libraries\n\nThe results of the test execution are written into an interpreter specific\ndirectory under the `atest/results` directory. Temporary outputs created\nduring the execution are created under the system temporary directory.\n\nTest data\n---------\n\nThe test data is divided into two sides, the execution side\n(`atest/robot <robot>`_ directory) and the test data side\n(`atest/testdata <testdata>`_ directory). The test data side contains test\ncases for different features. The execution side contains the actual acceptance\ntests that run the tests on the test data side and verify their results.\n\nThe basic mechanism to verify that a test case in the test data side is\nexecuted as expected is setting the expected status and possible error\nmessage in its documentation. By default tests are expected to pass, but\nhaving `FAIL` or `SKIP` (these and subsequent markers are case sensitive) in\nthe documentation changes the expectation. The text after the `FAIL` or `SKIP`\nmarker is the expected error message, which, by default, must match the actual\nerror exactly. If the error message starts with `REGEXP:`, `GLOB:` or\n`STARTS:`, the expected error is considered to be a regexp or glob pattern\nmatching the actual error, or to contain the beginning of the error. All\nother details can be tested also, but that logic is in the execution side.\n\nTest tags\n---------\n\nThe tests on the execution side (`atest/robot`) contain tags that are used\nto include or exclude them based on the platform and required dependencies.\nSelecting tests based on the platform is done automatically by the `<run.py>`__\nscript, but additional selection can be done by the user, for example, to\navoid running tests with dependencies_ that are not met.\n\nmanual\n  Require manual interaction from user. Used with Dialogs library tests.\n\ntelnet\n  Require a Telnet server with test account running on localhost. See\n  `Telnet tests`_ for details.\n\nno-ci\n  Tests which are not executed at continuous integration. Contains all tests\n  tagged with `manual` or `telnet`.\n\nrequire-yaml, require-lxml, require-screenshot\n  Require specified Python module or some other external tool to be installed.\n  Exclude like `--exclude require-lxml` if dependencies_ are not met.\n\nrequire-windows, require-py3.13, ...\n  Tests that require certain operating system or Python interpreter.\n  Excluded automatically outside these platforms.\n\nno-windows, no-osx, ...\n  Tests to be excluded on certain operating systems or Python interpreters.\n  Excluded automatically on these platforms.\n\nDependencies\n------------\n\nCertain Robot Framework features require optional external modules or tools\nto be installed, and naturally tests related to these features require same\nmodules/tools as well. This section lists what preconditions are needed to\nrun all tests successfully. See `Test tags`_ for instructions how to avoid\nrunning certain tests if all preconditions are not met.\n\nExecution side dependencies\n~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\n\nThe execution side has some dependencies listed in `<requirements-run.txt>`__\nthat needs to be installed before running tests. It is easiest to install\nthem all in one go using `pip`::\n\n    pip install -r atest/requirements-run.txt\n\nTest data side dependencies\n~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\n\nThe test data side contains the tests for various features and has more\ndependencies than the execution side.\n\nNeeded Python modules\n'''''''''''''''''''''\n\n- `docutils <http://docutils.sourceforge.net/>`_ is needed with tests related\n  to parsing test data in reStructuredText format and with Libdoc tests\n  for documentation in reST format.\n- `Pygments <http://pygments.org/>`_ is needed by Libdoc tests for syntax\n  highlighting.\n- `PyYAML <http://pyyaml.org/>`__ is required with tests related to YAML\n  variable files.\n- `Pillow <https://pypi.org/project/Pillow/>`_ for taking screenshots on Windows.\n- `lxml <http://lxml.de/>`__ is needed with XML library tests.\n\nIt is possible to install the above modules using `pip` individually, but\nit is easiest to use the provided `<requirements.txt>`__ file that installs\nneeded packages conditionally depending on the platform::\n\n    pip install -r atest/requirements.txt\n\nNotice that the lxml module may require compilation on Linux, which in turn\nmay require installing development headers of lxml dependencies. Alternatively\nlxml can be installed using a system package manager with a command like\n`sudo apt-get install python-lxml`.\n\nScreenshot module or tool\n'''''''''''''''''''''''''\n\nScreenshot library tests require a platform dependent module or tool that can\ntake screenshots. The above instructions already covered installing Pillow_\non Windows and on OSX it is possible to use tooling provided by the operating\nsystem automatically. For Linux alternatives consult the\n`Screenshot library documentation`__.\n\n__ http://robotframework.org/robotframework/latest/libraries/Screenshot.html\n\nSchema validation\n-----------------\n\noutput.xml schema\n~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\n\nCreated output.xml has a `schema <../doc/schema>`_ that can be tested as part of\nacceptance tests. The schema is always used to validate selected outputs (e.g. in\n`<robot/rebot/compatibility.robot>`_), but validating all outputs would slow down\nexecution a bit too much.\n\nIt is, however, possible to enable validating all outputs by setting\n`ATEST_VALIDATE_OUTPUT` environment variable to `TRUE` (case-insensitive)\nor by using `--schema-validation` (`-S`) option with `atest/run.py`.\nThis is recommended especially if the schema is updated or output.xml changed.\n\nLibdoc XML and JSON spec schemas\n~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~\n\nLibdoc can create spec files both in XML and JSON formats and they both have\n`schemas <../doc/schema>`_. All generated Libdoc specs are validated automatically\nin Libdoc tests.\n\nTelnet tests\n------------\n\nRunning telnet tests requires some extra setup. Instructions how to run them\ncan be found from `<testdata/standard_libraries/telnet/README.rst>`_.\nIf you don't want to run an unprotected telnet server on your machine, you can\nalways skip these tests by excluding tests with a tag `telnet` or `no-ci`.\n\nLicense and copyright\n---------------------\n\nAll content in the `atest` folder is under the following copyright::\n\n    Copyright 2008-2015 Nokia Networks\n    Copyright 2016-     Robot Framework Foundation\n\n    Licensed under the Apache License, Version 2.0 (the \"License\");\n    you may not use this file except in compliance with the License.\n    You may obtain a copy of the License at\n\n        http://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0\n\n    Unless required by applicable law or agreed to in writing, software\n    distributed under the License is distributed on an \"AS IS\" BASIS,\n    WITHOUT WARRANTIES OR CONDITIONS OF ANY KIND, either express or implied.\n    See the License for the specific language governing permissions and\n    limitations under the License.\n","numLines":257,"startLine":1,"totalLines":257}}}
